bug.short_desc: Buggy compile_et re-implementation seen on opensource.apple.com

long_desc.thetext:
Hi,
I hope this is just me!
I upgraded from an old IMAP version to 2.4.16, and started having horribly confusing problems. I traced it down to the fact that error codes in imap_err.h (and corresponding files) are longs (8 bytes) but the routines all work with int (4 bytes.) So, the error code is truncated and comparisons always fail. This got me on "append_check" (append.c) where "r" (an integer) is compared to IMAP_QUOTAROOT_NONEXISTENT (a long.) "r" is returned from quota_read (quota_db.c) where it is transferred as an int. So, this comparison always fails.
BTW, this only occurs because I don't have any quotas set!
I fixed this by going extensively through the code changing int's to long's whereever status was passed or compared - probably not the best fix.
A question I would ask is what can I do on next release? Is there a simple compile flag somebody knows about that causes ints to be 8 bytes?
I am on Linux 2.6.39.4, gcc-4.6.1. I'll be glad to answer any questions to support this bug.
Many thanks for the good work!
Best regards,
David.

Ok, that's an awful bug. I only work on 64 bit these days, which doesn't help!
Making this P1 and taking it now - it shouldn't be much work to fix, and it's worth pushing a new stable release out for!
Greg - CCing you because I'm sure you have strong opinions on what we should be doing to get our type system under control.

Thanks so much for looking into this!
I'm completely open to the notion that this is some strangeness in my system, but I don't think it is, at least in this particular case. I will admit that I've built my system from source since SLS 0.99. I am on a 64-bit X86_64, if that makes any difference. Compiling with 32-bit (-m32) or 64-bit (-m64) didn't help.
As far as I can tell things seem to have settled with GCC via C99 to where "int" is 4-bytes and "long" is 8-bytes on PCs(?) In any case, it seems that this is entrenched deeply into my kernel headers.
I wish there was a magic switch that said "make all integers 8 bytes now please," and believe me - I looked for it! Having said that, it is a generic matter of mixing "int" and "long."
Again, many thanks for looking into this!
Best regards,
David.

Thanks Bron. Hi David,
I don't think there's a problem with our code here, but probably something unusual with your environment that we're failing to handle.
The error codes produced by the compile_et program are quite carefully designed to fit into a signed 32b variable and still work despite any combination of C integer promotion that might sign-extend them to 64b or truncation down to 32b.
Just to double-check, I found a place in the code where an error code is checked for specifically:
# imap/quota.h 100 extern int quota_read(struct quota *quota, struct txn **tid, int wrlock);
# imap/mboxlist.c 2486 int mboxlist_setquotas(const char *root, 2487 int newquotas[QUOTA_NUMRESOURCES], int force) 2488 { ... 2492 int r; ... 2502 r = quota_read(&q, &tid, 1); ... 2521 if (r != IMAP_QUOTAROOT_NONEXISTENT) 2522 goto done; ... 2577 done: 2578 if (r && tid) quota_abort(&tid); 2579 if (!r) sync_log_quota(root); 2580 2581 return r; 2582 }
This code would fail to set a quota root if the error returned from quota_read() were miscompared at line 2521. The code is exercised by the Cassandane test Quota.using_storage (I checked this by adding syslog messages around that code and manually running the test). That test works on my 32b laptop; that test is run and passes every 12 hours on ci.cyrusimap.org, which is a 64b Linux VM. So I really don't think we're fundamentally broken in the way you describe.
So the interesting questions are, how and why is your environment different? Some obvious possibilities include a) your compiler is broken b) your compiler is being fed incorrect arguments c) the compile_et program is doing something strange when it generates the imap_err.h file. Note that compile_et might be either an installed system binary or one built from the source included with cyrus.
Can you please send me or attach here
- your config.status file - your build log - your imap/imap_err.h file - the executable resulting from building the small source file I will soon attach, with the same compiler and same options as your cyrus build - the output from running that executable.

That was kind of the conclusion I got to when I had to head out for the day for family stuff as well. compile_et on my 64 bit laptop generates numbers with a trailing L (sorry - not on the laptop now, so I can't give examples)
Hmm - looking at the tarball, we don't even generate imap_err.h in 'make dist', so it's not part of the tarball.
So yes, definitely looks like seeing the output would be useful!
Bron.

Created an attachment (id=1490) a.out (compiled t.c)
This is the compiled t.c executable.

Aha, your imap_err.h has
#define IMAP_INTERNAL (2390157824L)
and mine has
#define IMAP_INTERNAL (-1904809472L)
both of whose lower 32b are the sam value 8e76ea00, but yours will not survive C integral type promotion to long. That is curious, and smells like it would explain your observed problems.
The output from compiled t.c indicates that your compiler is doing the right thing with correctly formed error values, so I'm going to assume your build toolchain is sane.

so you're getting the compile_et program from your system's installed package, not Cyrus' own copy. What version is that package? I can report that comerr-dev 2.1-1.41.12-1ubuntu2 works.

For reference, here it the "compile_et." I updated it on 5/21/12, and will try to hark back to where / why I got it...

Uh oh....
Here is where I got it from!
http://opensource.apple.com/source/CyrusIMAP/CyrusIMAP-156/build_extras/bin/compile_et
I simply can't recall why I needed it at that moment. It replaced one from January 2006 in my /usr/bin that DID NOT work at all (for whatever I was using it for.)

(In reply to comment #19) > Uh oh.... > > Here is where I got it from! > > http://opensource.apple.com/source/CyrusIMAP/CyrusIMAP-156/build_extras/bin/compile_et
It's completely different from the e2fsprogs one. For one thing, it's a Perl script, but the e2fsprogs one is a shell script that calls an awk script.
http://e2fsprogs.sourceforge.net/
> > I simply can't recall why I needed it at that moment. It replaced one from > January 2006 in my /usr/bin that DID NOT work at all (for whatever I was using > it for.)
Well it seems this one doesn't work either, but the failure more is more subtle and occurs at runtime in generated code, which is arguably worse.

David, if you move aside the following
/usr/bin/compile_et /usr/include/et/com_err.h
and rebuild Cyrus from scratch, the Cyrus configure script should fall back on using it's own implementation of compile_et, which should work. If it doesn't, raise another bug.
Meanwhile I'll chase down the Apple guys and work out why they felt the need to publish a broken compile_et implementation.

Wow! Thanks for getting to the bottom of this Greg! As you note, what a PIA to find the issue subtly hidden in the bowels of the generated code! I put about a hundred "syslog"s in the code hunting it down :)
I just renamed the "compile_et" in /usr/bin, rebuilt, and now all is fine! I updated that compile_et about the time I tried to upgrade to 2.4.16 the first time (then went back and recompiled the older version too - big mistake.) Probably the 2006 compile_et failed and I went looking for a fresher copy, not realizing that there was already a compatible one in the distro.
I certainly appreciate your effort to track this down! I didn't realize there was one in e2fsprogs, but I'm starting to think it doesn't belong in /usr/bin at all, as there are so many bad copies around. Who knows which ones are tuned for which software packages!
Sorry to impugn Cyrus IMAP. I've used the software for many years and never had an issue at all, hence it was hard to figure how I could be the only guy around having problems like the type mismatch, which was on surface seems to be a potentially very serious matter. I simply didn't realize that those files had been generated. While they do appear to have type mismatches, apparently that's factored in so it won't cause misbehaviour.
Again, many thanks for your attention to this. I hope the Apple guys will pull down that bad version so that nobody else goes through this, and it is very nice that you carry a solid pack of these in the distro!
Best regards,
David.

I just sent this patch to Apple. It makes their compile_et work correctly when run on either 32b or 64b Perl.

Very very nice!
Many thanks Greg!
David.

Four weeks ago, I did not report this to Apple because they made me register as an Apple developer to do so. That's right, they make you give them a bunch of personal details in order to report a bug in open source code that they didn't write but publish on their website. Meh.
Anyway, today I got to the point of deciding that I needed to register as an Apple developer for other reasons, and so the first thing I did was actually report this bug. So it's Apple bug #11972600. I don't seem to be able to provide a stable URL to page that anyone except I can read, or I would.
